<FONT CLASS="ArticleSource"><BIG>Interview:</BIG></FONT> 
<FONT CLASS="ArticleHead"><BIG>Lumthemad Moves On</BIG></FONT>
<FONT CLASS="ArticleAuthorLight">&nbsp;filed by </FONT><FONT CLASS="ArticleAuthor">Tann</FONT>
<DIV ALIGN=RIGHT>
<FONT CLASS=ArticleTime>09/25/2001 09:27 PM CDT</FONT>
<DIV ALIGN=LEFT>
<FONT CLASS=ArticleText>
<B>Tann:</B>  Why the request for a new name for the site? Readers recognize that Lum the person has moved on, but why does he feel his &quot;legacy&quot; needs to end? <p><B>Eldin:</B> The concern wasn't with the legacy of the site. The problem is that, to a large portion of the community, Scott Jennings is Lum. Not Lum, but LUM. And, with the name of Lumthemad.net, many people were associating the opinions of the writers on the site with those of Scott/Lum. Since he works for Mythic now, it would be problematic to have anything we say reflect on Scott and/or his company. So, changing the name of the site to slownewsday.net seemed like in the best interests of Scott, us, and the company he works for. <p><B>Tann:</B> Lumthemad has been a consistent source for reporting opinions and editorials about the gaming community that while at times are harsh, often reflect a true sense of the gaming community's feelings. With the changes the site will be undergoing, will the focus remain on these type of editorials and opinions?<p><B>Eldin:</B> Absolutely. Right now, the site is exploring options to expand beyond the internet medium. We have had several offers which I can't going into great detail about right now. However, the nature of the site will not be changing.<br> <br><B>Tann:</B> Will your site have the staff/editors still passionate and interested in submitting the high quality articles your readers have come to expect?<p><B>Eldin:</B> *laughs* Well, we hope so. The majority of the current staff is staying on with the new site. Myschyf herself will continue writing guest rants. Right now, we're currently going through many submissions in order to find new writers for the site. We would like more content on the site, but we need to ensure that quantity does not affect quality.<br> <br><B>Tann:</B> Lumthemad has actually managed to come up with a financial paradigm that works. Donations and advertising dollars have allowed the site to stay solvent. Do you foresee problems for what appears to finally be a successful model?<p><B>Eldin:</B> Right now, the site looks to be stable for at least six months to a year. We have many, many offers from advertisers willing to pay us well to carry their products (we have a much higher than average click-through rate on the ad banners displayed on the site). Along with our future expansion, money isn't much of a concern for us right now.<p><B>Tann:</B> Look into your crystal ball, MMORPG's are due out or in development that are going to create excitement in the genre like never before. Five years from now, when we look back, what game is going to still be around, and what game are we going to be basing comparing all others too<p><B>Eldin:</B> It's very difficult to say. Before, most online games had a much smaller audience which made it easier to maintain a virtual world for years on end. Now, companies pour more and more resources into succesor games (AC2, rumors of EQ2, and the now defunct UO2). I'd like to say EQ and UO will most likely be around in 5 years. However, when companies make successor games to them, I'm not sure if the companies will close those games down over time in order to steer customers to the newer products. It sounds insidious almost, but stranger things have happened.<p>As things stand now, in the industry, EQ, the great money-maker, is the measure. Most of the companies currently out there are hoping to repeat EQ's success.<p><B>Tann:</B> How much play time can you and the staff actually get, and do the research and articles your site requires? Your articles are informed and as I mentioned earlier representative, but how much time does that leave to just kick back and have fun?<p><B>Eldin:</B> *laughs* Not much, unfortunately. We all have very busy real life jobs, in addition to writing and researching for the site. I don't know about my fellow writers, but I sneak off in the middle of the night a few times a week and spend a few hours on whatever online game I'm playing at the time. That way, I get in about 15 hours of gaming a week. Sleep comes usually around the time I'm supposed to be doing other things, like eating.<br>Researching varies. Sometimes, we'll see something and instantly have an article appear. Other times, we have to spend hours scouring the net, reading message boards, asking questions, sending e-mails, doing interviews, etc. I've written articles in 15 minutes, and I've spent as much as 12 hours of research on others. There's no set timeframe for writing and researching.<p><B>Tann:</B> What direction do you have planned to take the new site? Will it continue to consist of rants/editorials about timely gaming issues, and will you be able to expand to include the latest cycle of MMORPGs?<p><B>Eldin:</B> The site will consist mainly of rants and editorials, however don't be surprised if general news doesn't sneak in here and there. We plan on covering the second generation of MMORPGs. Right now, we write about WWIIOL and AO, and are waiting for Atriarch, Neocron, AC2, SWG, and many other future titles to be released. <p><B>Tann:</B> Have you decided on the new name? What time frame should readers expect for the move?<p><B>Eldin:</B> We decided on <B>slownewsday.net</B>. It's a bit of an inside joke (people teasing us would sometimes write &quot;Slow news day?&quot; on the boards. Eventually, people started doing it so much that we have to outlaw it and ban people who used it).  Lumthemad.net's last day will be September 30th, 2001. The new site will go up on October 1st.
</FONT>
</TD>
</TR>
